<font color="#FF0000">REMBERING  VIET NAM</font><br>
<tt>Sat Jan 11  0:16:53 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I don't let go of Viet Nam. I think about it or some part of it every day. This is ok for me. I have no nightmares, hatered, or regrets. Because I never did any thing that I am ashamed of. <br>
 I was decorated for valor because I stayed alive. I did what I had to do to stay alive. Theres no shame in that. I've never told anyone that I'm whats called a hero. My wife found out when she found my awards twenty years ago. She never asked what I did. I couldn't tell her if she had. I told her I had a different life then. She was protesting in 1970 and I was doing what I was doing. Just different lives.<br>
 I think about Viet Nam every day. I think about the combat. But thats mine to think about in the privacy of my own mine. I pass on to others the stories of jungle living. Living with the Vietnamess in a village. Stand downs in Chu Li. The bad floor shows, whores and getting loaded. But most of all I talk about the FUN I had. The best fun I've ever had in my life.<br>
 I can't hate. And I don't regret anything. I do know that me and the other Grunts have done things that most people have or never will do. This makes us very special. We have some thing thats our very own. <br>
 Don't try to forget it. It was a differnt life thats all.
